      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Top Temperatures in the Database\n\n| Temperature (°C) | Count | Percentage |\n|------------------:|------:|----------:|\n| 25.0 | 67,237 | 85.04% |\n| 20.0 | 6,845 | 8.66% |\n| 37.0 | 1,699 | 2.15% |\n| 30.0 | 919 | 1.16% |\n| 35.0 | 488 | 0.62% |\n| 18.0 | 482 | 0.61% |\n\nThe overwhelming dominance of 25 °C reflects its status as the standard reference temperature in solution thermodynamics. The next most common temperature, 20 °C (8.7%), is a legacy of older European laboratory conventions, while 37 °C (2.2%) corresponds to physiological temperature — measurements relevant to bioinorganic and medicinal chemistry applications.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes)*",
